<dl id="n52178g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n52" href="#n52178g">N52 (VI.B.42)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n52all.htm#n52178g"> 178(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Youd / nat heed thet fert? / Fulgitudar jist / rowdownen tonuit. <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n52178g"><li>FW 258.03f </li><li><a href="../../flex/kg/lexkg.htm#n52178g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kg/l39kg.htm#n52178g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n52178g">MS BL 47477-186</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:275 <a name="kad8" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kgd6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kg/kgd6.htm#n52178g">Draft: II.1&sect;7.6</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n42148e" href="n42all.htm#n42148e">N42 (VI.B.31):148(e)</a> and <a name="n33022c" href="n33all.htm#n33022c">N33 (VI.B.4):022(c)</a>. Not hear that far(t)? Also Latin <i>fulgor</i>: lightning; <i>tonuit</i>: it thundered. According to a tradition (which has been disputed: see <cite>Notes and Queries</cite>, <a href=" https://books.google.ie/books?id=YC217MX35oIC&pg=PA461&dq=fortitudo+eius+rhodum+tenuit&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwickq2Plq7pAhUxTxUIHTBmDaYQ6AEIZzAH#v=onepage&q=fortitudo%20eius%20rhodum%20tenuit&f=false" target="_blank">4th s. VI Nov. 26, 1870, p. 461</a>), the Knights of the Order of the Hospital of St John of Jerusalem conferred their cross, with the device <mark>F.E.R.T.</mark> (<mark><i>Fortitudo Ejus Rhodum Tenuit</i></mark>: his bravery has held Rhodes), on Amadeus V, Count of Savoy (1249Â–1323) following his victory over the Saracens at the siege of Rhodes in 1315. </mm> </dd></dl>
